# Calculate silhouette width for many k using PAM

sil_width <- c(NA)

for(i in 2:10){
  
  pam_fit <- pam(euclidean.dissimilarity.mtrx,
                 diss = TRUE,
                 k = i)
  
  sil_width[i] <- pam_fit$silinfo$avg.width
  
}

# Plot sihouette width (higher is better; in our data we have a peak at 2 clusters)

plot(1:10, sil_width,
     xlab = "Number of clusters",
     ylab = "Silhouette Width")
lines(1:10, sil_width)

#Using two clusters in our data
pam_fit <- pam(euclidean.dissimilarity.mtrx , diss = TRUE, k = 2)

pam_results <- metadata %>%
  dplyr::select(-SampleID) %>%
  mutate(cluster = pam_fit$clustering) %>%
  group_by(cluster) %>%
  do(the_summary = summary(.))

pam_results$the_summary

tsne_obj <- Rtsne(euclidean.dissimilarity.mtrx, is_distance = TRUE, perplexity = 14)
tsne_data <- tsne_obj$Y %>%
  data.frame() %>%
  setNames(c("X", "Y")) %>%
  mutate(cluster = factor(pam_fit$clustering),
         name = metadata$SampleID)

write.csv(tsne_data, "/Users/vupadhyay/Documents/Work/UCSF/TurnbaughLab/IDEO/RMDs_and_outputs/Clustering_Analyses/DietaryQuestionaireData/Outputs/ClusteringSubjectsDHQ3.csv")

ggplot(aes(x = X, y = Y), data = tsne_data) +
  geom_point(aes(fill = cluster), shape=21, size=2) + scale_fill_discrete(name="Legend", labels=c("DClust-1", "DClust-2")) + theme_bw() + xlab("tSNE-1") + ylab("tSNE-2") + theme(axis.title = element_blank(), axis.text = element_text(size = 14), legend.text = element_text(size = 14), legend.title = element_text(size = 14), legend.position = c(.9,.875), legend.background = element_rect(linetype = 2, size = 0.5, colour = 1))

#####Is clustering driven by vegetables?#####

#Now repeat the same steps with no metabolic data
euclidean.dissimilarity.mtrx.noveggie <- daisy(DHQ3.noveggie[,-1], metric = c("euclidean"))
## Warning in daisy(DHQ3.noveggie[, -1], metric = c("euclidean")): binary
## variable(s) 180, 221 treated as interval scaled
euclidean_mat.noveggie <- as.matrix(euclidean.dissimilarity.mtrx.noveggie)

# Calculate silhouette width for many k using PAM to see if clustering is preserved with removal of macronutrient data

sil_width.noveggie <- c(NA)

for(i in 2:10){
  
  pam_fit.noveggie <- pam(euclidean.dissimilarity.mtrx.noveggie,
                 diss = TRUE,
                 k = i)
  
  sil_width.noveggie[i] <- pam_fit.noveggie$silinfo$avg.width
  
}

# Plot sihouette width (higher is better; in our data we have a peak at 2 clusters)

plot(1:10, sil_width.noveggie,
     xlab = "Number of clusters",
     ylab = "Silhouette Width")
lines(1:10, sil_width.noveggie)

#Using two clusters in our data
pam_fit.noveggie <- pam(euclidean_mat.noveggie, diss = TRUE, k = 2)

  mutate(cluster = pam_fit$clustering) %>%
  group_by(cluster) %>%
  do(the_summary = summary(.))

euclidean_mat.noveggie.no36 <- as.matrix(euclidean.dissimilarity.mtrx.noveggie.no36)

# Calculate silhouette width for many k using PAM to see if clustering is preserved with removal of macronutrient data

sil_width.noveggie.no36 <- c(NA)

for(i in 2:10){
  
  pam_fit.noveggie.no36 <- pam(euclidean.dissimilarity.mtrx.noveggie.no36,
                 diss = TRUE,
                 k = i)
  
  sil_width.noveggie.no36[i] <- pam_fit.noveggie.no36$silinfo$avg.width
  
}

# Plot sihouette width (higher is better; in our data we have a peak at 2 clusters)

plot(1:10, sil_width.noveggie.no36,
     xlab = "Number of clusters",
     ylab = "Silhouette Width")
lines(1:10, sil_width.noveggie.no36)

# Calculate silhouette width for many k using PAM

sil_width.asa <- c(NA)

for(i in 2:10){
  
  pam_fit.asa <- pam(euclidean.dissimilarity.mtrx.asa,
                 diss = TRUE,
                 k = i)
  
  sil_width.asa[i] <- pam_fit.asa$silinfo$avg.width
  
}

# Plot sihouette width (higher is better; in our data we have a peak at 2 clusters)

plot(1:10, sil_width.asa,
     xlab = "Number of clusters",
     ylab = "Silhouette Width")
lines(1:10, sil_width.asa)

  data.frame() %>%
  setNames(c("X", "Y")) %>%
  mutate(cluster = factor(pam_fit.asa$clustering),
         name = metadata$SampleID)

#Here we are making a table of the features driving clustering

Metadata.ClusterAssignment$ClusterVar <- factor(Metadata.ClusterAssignment$cluster, levels = c(1,2,3),labels = c("DClust-1", "DClust-2", "P-value"))

rndr <- function(x, name, ...) {
    if (length(x) == 0) {
        y <- Metadata.ClusterAssignment[[name]]
        s <- rep("", length(render.default(x=y, name=name, ...)))
        if (is.numeric(y)) {
            p <- t.test(y ~ Metadata.ClusterAssignment$ClusterVar)$p.value
        } else {
            p <- chisq.test(table(y, droplevels(Metadata.ClusterAssignment$ClusterVar)))$p.value
        }
        s[2] <- sub("<", "&lt;", format.pval(p, digits=2, eps=0.001))
        s
    } else {
        render.default(x=x, name=name, ...)
    }
}

#This is a labeling loop...not really sure why you need this; if you exclude it it put's (N=0) underneath the P-value column
rndr.strat <- function(label, n, ...) {
    ifelse(n==0, label, render.strat.default(label, n, ...))
}
